[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(22) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Sons of Belial.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—It is only by a deeply-rooted misconception that Belial is written with a capital. The word is not the name (as is supposed) of an evil spirit, but an ordinary noun, “sons of worthlessness,” ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "i.e., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "“worthless fellows.” (See ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 13:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 18:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) Later (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Corinthians 6:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") it became a kind of proper name. Josephus dishonestly suppresses all the darkest features of the story (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Antt. v.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " 11, § 7).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Beset the house.—There is a close resemblance to the equally hideous narrative of Genesis 19:8.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Beset the house.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—There is a close resemblance to the equally hideous narrative of ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Genesis 19:8",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Beat at the door.—The word implies continuous knocking and gradual increase of noise (Song of Solomon 5:2). We cannot wonder that the intense horror excited by this scene of infamy lasted for centuries afterwards. “They have deeply corrupted themselves, as in the days of Gibeah” (Hosea 9:9). “O Israel, thou hast sinned from the days of Gibeah” (Hosea 10:9).",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Beat at the door.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—The word implies continuous knocking and gradual increase of noise (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Song of Solomon 5:2",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). We cannot wonder that the intense horror excited by this scene of infamy lasted for centuries afterwards. “They have deeply corrupted themselves, as in the days of Gibeah” (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Hosea 9:9",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). “O Israel, thou hast sinned from the days of Gibeah” (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Hosea 10:9",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ").",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "“And when night",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Darkens the streets, then wander forth the sons",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Of Belial, flown with insolence and wine.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Witness the streets of Sodom, and that night",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In Gibeah, when the hospitable door",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Exposed a matron to avoid worse rape.”—Milton.",
        "children": [
