        "text": "filii Belial",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", followed by the AV., RV. In the N.T. Belial has become a synonym for Satan, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 6:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and in this sense the word is used in apocalyptic literature, e.g. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Jubilees, Test. xii. Patriarchs, Sibylline Oracles",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Although Belial is not interpreted as a proper name till a late period, yet originally perhaps it had this significance. Cheyne (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Encycl. Bibl",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". col. 526 f.) seeks the origin of the name in popular mythology, and adopts the derivation ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "belî-ya‘aleh",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " = ‘(that from which) one comes not up again,’ i.e Sheol, or the demon of the abyss; cf. the Babylonian name for the underworld ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "irṣît la tari",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " = ‘land without return.’ This explanation is certainly appropriate in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 18:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " = ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 22:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "floods of Belial",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and, with an extension of meaning, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 41:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 101:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " lit. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "a thing of B.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nahum 1:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " RVm.; we have then to suppose that the abyss, or the demon of the abyss, came to represent a power or quality of gross wickedness. Cheyne’s view is ingenious and we must allow that the usual explanation rests upon a doubtful etymology.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "beset the house … know him",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The same words in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 19:4-5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It looks as if the present narrative had been deliberately conformed here and there to the description of the immorality of the Sodomites. This is certainly the case in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Jdg 19:24",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Jdg 19:24",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where the phrases are identical with those in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 19:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Some scholars think that the present verse originally read ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Bring forth the woman … that we may know her",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", chiefly on the ground that in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jdg 20:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the Levite does not allude to the particular crime mentioned in the text as it stands, but declares that the men of Gibeah wanted to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "slay",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " him. The inconsistency may be more apparent than real. After what happened to the woman, the Levite might well assert that the intention was to kill him, while he would hardly repeat the expression used here.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 22.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Making their hearts merry",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - as in vers. 6, 9, and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 16:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ruth 3:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". But there is nothing in the expression implying any excess in drinking. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Bring forth the man",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The abandoned character of the men appears in this, that not only did they offer no hospitality to the stranger themselves, but were ready to violate the sanctity of the hospitality of the old man's house by their brutal violence. There must have been a fearful absence of all law and order and government when such deeds could be done without any interference on the part of magistrate or elder or ruler of any kind. The singular resemblance of the whole narrative to that in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". suggests that the Israelites by their contact with the accursed Canaanites had reduced themselves to the level of Sodom and Gomorrah. Surely this shows the wisdom of the command to destroy utterly the workers of abomination. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Sons of Belial",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". See ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 20:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where the same Hebrew phrase is rendered ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "children of Belial.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Belial in this common phrase is not a proper name, but a noun meaning ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "worthlessness. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Sons or men of Belial means worthless fellows. Judges 19:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Whilst they were enjoying themselves, some worthless men of the city surrounded the house, knocking continuously at the door (התדּפּק, a form indicative of gradual increase), and demanding of the master of the house that he would bring out the man who had entered his house, that they might know him,-the very same demand that the Sodomites had made of Lot (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 19:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".). The construct state בני־בליּעל אנשׁי is used instead of בּני־בל אנשׁים (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 13:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.), because בליעל בני is regarded as one idea: people of worthless fellows. Other cases of the same kind are given by Ewald, Lehrb. 289, c.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]